//================Trie

A Trie (pronounced "try") is a special tree-like data structure used to store and search strings (words) efficiently.

//=====What are the types of Trie?

Answer:

There are several types of Trie:

Standard Trie (Prefix Trie) – Stores words character by character for efficient prefix searching.
Suffix Trie – Stores all suffixes of a string and is used for pattern matching.
Compressed Trie (Radix Trie) – Merges single-child nodes to reduce memory usage.
Ternary Search Trie (TST) – Combines features of a Trie and Binary Search Tree.
Patricia Trie – An optimized compressed Trie commonly used in networking.
What are the advantages of Trie?

Answer:

//====The main advantages of a Trie are:

Fast insertion and search operations.
Efficient prefix-based searching.
Ideal for autocomplete and suggestion systems.
No hash collisions unlike hash tables.
Words can be retrieved in lexicographical (dictionary) order.
What are the applications of Trie?

Answer:

//============================Trie is commonly used in:

Autocomplete systems.
Spell checkers.
Dictionaries and word lookup applications.
Search engine suggestions.
Contact search applications.
IP routing tables in networking.
Pattern matching and string processing.